description.plain:
Keith Lionel Urban is a Australian-American Country singer and songwriter he was born on October 26th 1967. In Whangarei New Zealand. He is the youngest son of Marianne and Robert Urban.
He has a older brother named Shane.
He started his career in Australia.
In the 1990s he moved to America in 1992. He had drug and alcohol problems but after going through rehab 3 times. He is sober and has been for 12 years.
He has won multiple awards for his music and has a total of 10 studio albums.

songs.full_title: Blue Ain't Your Color by Keith Urban
songs.title: Blue Ain’t Your Color

description.plain:
On “Blue Ain’t Your Color,” Keith Urban offers a fresh take on a classic sound. The song pairs sad-sack lyrics with a waltzing beat—nothing is more country than that. Also, there’s alcohol—another country trope that Urban folds into a modern-sounding composition. The song appears on Urban’s experimental ninth album, 2016’s ‘Ripcord.’ Urban says he didn’t want this song to sound like a “typical sonic presentation of a waltz.”

I wanted to try and mess with that a little bit, which is what drove the drum machine. Machinery drives the song, because you don’t normally have machinery in a waltz, unless you’ve got an organ.

Urban gave the song its “own sonic thumbprint” by experimenting with combinations of electronic drums and organic Telecaster guitar. He told the Boot it was a “very, very stark, minimalistic way of recording,” inspired by the classic country records of Don Williams. Urban had learned about Williams through his father, Bob Urban, who died during the making of ‘Ripcord’ and wound up influencing the record.

Urban is a fan of Williams’ “attitude”—the veteran Texas singer believes “the song is the picture, and the record is the frame.” Urban:


You’ve got to find the right frame, not too much and not too little, to make the picture really work.

So for the songs that don’t need much, like ‘Blue Ain’t Your Color,’ my dad’s record collection obviously has informed that a lot.

songs.title: Female

description.plain:
“Female” was written by Shane McAnally, Ross Copperman, and Nicolle Galyon, and performed by Keith Urban. The song was written around three weeks prior to its November 8, 2017 release and was inspired by the Harvey Weinstein sexual assault claims.

Songwriter Ross Copperman talked about the song in an interview at the 2017 BMI Country Awards stating,

We actually wrote a song three weeks ago called “Female”. It’s from the Weinstein announcement. We’re in a room and we’re like, ‘What can we do about this?’ And that’s the one thing we can do is write songs.

This song was Performed at the CMA-Country Music Awards

songs.full_title: John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16 by Keith Urban
songs.title: John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16

description.plain:
“John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16” is the lead single from Keith Urban’s ninth studio album. After hearing a demo of the song by songwriters Josh Osborne, Shane McAnally, and Ross Copperman, Urban previewed the song acoustically at the 2015 Country Radio Seminar to great listener feedback. He said the track “resonated deeply” with him immediately, thanks in part to the “the poetic use of the three Johns and what each represents to me.”

“John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16” was sent to country radio on June 8, 2015, a day before its digital release.  Urban also performed the track live on the 2015 CMT Music Awards on June 10, 2015.

Cowriter Shane McAnally explained the meaning of the three Johns to Billboard:

John Cougar references all the sort of sexual tension of teenage angst all of us were growing up in. John Deere represents the way that our parents worked and what we saw living in the country, and of course [there’s] the element of religion. And [there’s] irony in John Cougar starting the line, and John 3:16 ending the line because that was the push and pull of that teenage thing.
